[src:web-hid/api-hid] This feature is not Baseline because it does not work in some of the most widely-used browsers.
[src:web-hid/api-hid] The **`HID`** interface provides methods for connecting to *HID devices*, listing attached HID devices and event handlers for connected HID devices.
[src:web-hid/api-hid] Returns a `Promise` that resolves with an array of connected HID devices that the user has previously been granted access to in response to a `requestDevice()` call.
[src:web-hid/api-hid] Returns a `Promise` that resolves with an array of connected `HIDDevice` objects.
[src:web-hid/api-hid] Calling this function will trigger the user agent's permission flow in order to gain permission to access one selected device from the returned list of devices.
[src:web-hid/api-hid] Fired when an HID device is disconnected.
[src:web-hid/api-hiddevice] The **`HIDDevice`** interface of the WebHID API represents a HID Device.
[src:web-hid/api-hiddevice] It provides properties for accessing information about the device, methods for opening and closing the connection, and the sending and receiving of reports.
[src:web-hid/api-hiddevice] This interface also inherits properties from `EventTarget`.
[src:web-hid/api-hiddevice] Returns a `Boolean`, true if the device has an open connection.
[src:web-hid/api-hiddevice] Returns the productId of the HID device.
[src:web-hid/api-hiddevice] Returns a string containing the product name of the HID device.
[src:web-hid/api-hiddevice] Returns an array of report formats for the HID device.
[src:web-hid/api-hiddevice] Fires when a report is sent from the device.
[src:web-hid/api-hiddevice] This interface also inherits methods from `EventTarget`.
[src:web-hid/api-hiddevice] Opens a connection to this HID device, and returns a `Promise` which resolves once the connection has been successful.
[src:web-hid/api-hiddevice] Closes the connection to this HID device, and returns a `Promise` which resolves once the connection has been closed.
[src:web-hid/api-hiddevice] Closes the connection to this HID device and resets access permission, and returns a `Promise` which resolves once the permission was reset.
[src:web-hid/api-hiddevice] Sends an output report to this HID Device, and returns a `Promise` which resolves once the report has been sent.
[src:web-hid/api-hiddevice] Sends a feature report to this HID device, and returns a `Promise` which resolves once the report has been sent.
[src:web-hid/api-hiddevice] Receives a feature report from this HID device in the form of a `Promise` which resolves with a `DataView`.
[src:web-hid/api-hiddevice] This allows typed access to the contents of this message.
[src:web-hid/api-hiddevice] The following example demonstrates listening for an `inputreport` event that will allow the application to detect which button is pressed on a Joy-Con Right device.
[src:web-hid/api-hiddevice] In the following example `sendFeatureReport` is used to make a device blink.
[src:web-hid/api-hiddevice] You can see more examples, and live demos in the article Connecting to uncommon HID devices.
[src:web-hid/api-webhid-api] A Human Interface Device (HID) is a type of device that takes input from or provides output to humans.
[src:web-hid/api-webhid-api] It also refers to the HID protocol, a standard for bi-directional communication between a host and a device that is designed to simplify the installation procedure.
[src:web-hid/api-webhid-api] The HID protocol was originally developed for USB devices but has since been implemented over many other protocols, including Bluetooth.
[src:web-hid/api-webhid-api] Provides methods for connecting to HID devices, listing attached HID devices and event handlers for connected HID devices.
[src:web-hid/api-webhid-api] It's possible for a single physical device to be represented by multiple `HIDDevice` objects.
[src:web-hid/api-webhid-api] Passed to the `HIDDevice` `inputreport` event when an input report is received from any associated HID device.
[src:web-hid/api-webhid-api] Passed to `HID` `connect` and `disconnect` events when a device is connected or disconnected.
[src:web-hid/api-webhid-api] You can connect to a device with the `requestDevice()` method.
[src:web-hid/api-webhid-api] In this case, we select from all the available devices.
[src:web-hid/api-webhid-api] We can retrieve all the devices the website has been granted access to previously and log the device names to the console.
[src:web-hid/api-webhid-api] We can register event listeners for disconnection of any HID devices.
[src:web-hid/hidinputreportevent] The **`HIDInputReportEvent`** interface of the WebHID API is passed to `inputreport` event of `HIDDevice` when an input report is received from any associated HID device.
[src:web-hid/hidinputreportevent] A `DataView` containing the data from the input report, excluding the `reportId` if the HID interface uses report IDs.
[src:web-hid/hidinputreportevent] The `HIDDevice` instance that represents the HID interface that sent the input report.
[src:web-hid/hidinputreportevent] The one-byte identification prefix for this report, or 0 if the HID interface does not use report IDs.
[src:web-hid/hidinputreportevent] The following example demonstrates listening for an `inputReport` that will allow the application to detect which button is pressed on a Joy-Con Right device.
[src:web-hid/human-interface-device] A **human interface device** (**HID**) is a type of computer device usually used by humans that takes input from or provides output to humans.
[src:web-hid/human-interface-device] The term "HID" most commonly refers to the USB HID specification.
[src:web-hid/human-interface-device] The term was coined by Mike Van Flandern of Microsoft when he proposed that the USB committee create a Human Input Device class working group.
[src:web-hid/human-interface-device] The working group was renamed as the Human Interface Device class at the suggestion of Tom Schmidt of DEC because the proposed standard supported bidirectional communication.
[src:web-hid/human-interface-device] A working committee with representatives from several prominent companies developed the HID standard.
[src:web-hid/human-interface-device] The list of participants appears in the "Device Class Definition for Human Interface Devices (HID)" document.
[src:web-hid/human-interface-device] SIM was also self-describing and extensible, however it was more focused on SIMulation devices used for VR and motion capture.
[src:web-hid/human-interface-device] After comparing notes at a Consumer Game Developer Conference, Steve and Mike agreed to collaborate on a new standard for the emerging Universal Serial Bus (USB).
[src:web-hid/human-interface-device] Since HID's original definition over USB, HID is now also used in other computer communication buses.
[src:web-hid/human-interface-device] This enables HID devices that traditionally were only found on USB to also be used on alternative buses.
[src:web-hid/human-interface-device] This is done since existing support for USB HID devices can typically be adapted much faster than having to invent an entirely new protocol to support mouse, touchpad, keyboards, and the like.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] The USB HID class is defined in a number of documents provided by the USB Implementers Forum's Device Working Group.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] The primary document used to describe the USB HID class is the Device Class Definition for HID 1.11.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] The USB HID class describes devices used with nearly every modern computer.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] Many predefined functions exist in the USB HID class.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] These functions allow hardware manufacturers to design a product to USB HID class specifications and expect it to work with any software that also meets these specifications.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] The same HID protocol is used unmodified in Bluetooth human interface devices.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] The Bluetooth profile specification only points readers to the USB HID documentation.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] In this sense those devices also belong to the USB HID class.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] Keyboards are a common kind of USB HID class device.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] The USB HID class keyboard is normally designed with an IN endpoint that communicates keystrokes to the computer and an OUT endpoint that communicates the status of the keyboard's LEDs from the computer to the keyboard.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] The PC 97 standard requires that a computer's BIOS must detect and work with USB HID class keyboards that are designed to be used during the boot process.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] Some keyboards implement the *USB Boot Keyboard* profile specified in the USB Device Class Definition for Human Interface Devices (HID) v1.11 and are explicitly configured to use the boot protocol.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] This profile is intended to allow the BIOS to handle a USB keyboard in the absence of a USB-aware operating system.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] However, keyboards in non-boot mode are free to implement an alternative HID profile.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] The above-mentioned behavior is in contrast to the PS/2 interface, which supports *n*-key rollover (NKRO) for keyboards capable of supporting it.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] Computer mouse is another common USB HID class device.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] USB HID mice can range from single-button simple devices to multi-button compound devices.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] Most modern operating systems ship with drivers for standard HID mouse designs (the most common modern mouse design has two dedicated buttons and a mouse wheel that doubles as the third button); mice with extended functionality require custom drivers from the manufacturer.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] USB mice have lower latencies than PS/2 mice because standard USB mice are often polled at a default rate of 125 Hz while standard PS/2 mice send interrupts at a default rate of 100 Hz when they have data to send to the computer.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] Also, USB mice do not cause the USB controller to interrupt the system when they have no status change to report according to the USB HID specification's default profile for mouse devices.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] Both PS/2 and USB allow the sample rate to be overridden, with PS/2 supporting a sampling rate of up to 200 Hz and USB supporting a polling rate up to 1 kHz given the USB mouse runs at full-speed or up to 8kHz given the USB mouse runs at high-speed.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] Modern game controllers and joysticks are often USB HID class devices.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] Unlike legacy game port devices, USB HID class game devices do not normally require proprietary drivers to function.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] Nearly all game devices will function using onboard drivers as long as the device is designed around the drivers and the USB HID class specifications.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] The USB HID class specifications allow for myriad other devices under the USB HID class.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] Some examples are automobile simulation controllers, exercise machines, telephony devices, thermometers, audio controls and medical instrumentation.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] Even uninterruptible power supplies and software protection dongles declare themselves under this class, despite the fact they often have no human interface at all.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] Any device can be a USB HID class device as long as a designer meets the USB HID class logical specifications.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] This is not to say that there is no need to ship drivers for these devices, nor that an operating system will immediately recognize the device.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] This only means that the device can declare itself under the human interface device class.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] As a partial countermeasure, PS/2 peripherals may be used instead together with disabling all USB ports.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] One of the benefits of a well-defined specification like the USB HID class is the abundance of device drivers available in most modern operating systems.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] The USB HID class devices and their basic functions are defined in USB-IF documentation without any specific software in mind.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] Because of these generic descriptions, it is easy for operating system designers to include functioning drivers for devices such as keyboards, mice, and other generic human interface devices.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] The inclusion of these generic drivers allows for faster deployment of devices and easier installation by end-users.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] Windows 98 was the first version of Windows that supported USB HID.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] The USB human interface device class can be used to describe both device and interface classes.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] The interface class is used when a USB device can contain more than one function.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] It is possible, therefore, to have USB devices with two different interfaces at the same time (for example, a USB telephone may use a keypad covered by the HID class and a speaker covered by the USB communications device class).
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] The interface devices are also defined with subclass descriptors.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] The subclass descriptor is used to declare a device bootable.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] A boot device meets a minimum adherence to a basic protocol and will be recognized by a computer's BIOS.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] Each USB HID interface communicates with the host using either a *control* pipe or an *interrupt* pipe.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] *Isochronous* and *bulk* pipes are not used in HID class devices.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] Both IN and OUT control transfers are required for enumeration; only an IN interrupt transfer is required for HID reports.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] OUT interrupt transfers are optional in HID-class devices.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] The USB HID class requires that every device describes how it will communicate with the host device in order to accurately predict and define all current and future human interface devices.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] During enumeration the device describes how its reports are to be structured so that the host device can properly prepare to receive this information.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] The host periodically polls the device's interrupt IN endpoint during operation.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] When the device has data to send it forms a report and sends it as a reply to the poll token.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] Common devices such as keyboards and mice send reports that are compliant with standards set by the USB Implementers Forum (USB-IF).
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] When a vendor makes a custom USB HID class device, the reports formed by the device need to match the report description given during enumeration and the driver installed on the host system.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] In this way it is possible for the USB HID class to be extremely flexible.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] There are two levels of APIs related to USB HID: the USB level and the operating system level.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] At the USB level, there is a protocol for devices to announce their capabilities and the operating system to parse the data it gets.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] The operating system then offers a higher-level view to applications, which do not need to include support for individual devices but for classes of devices.
[src:web-hid/usb-human-interface-device-class] This abstraction layer allows a game to work with any USB controller, for example, even ones created after the game.
